    <thetext>(from bug 331649 comment 50):

Consider a class with two final fields:

class C {
   final Object o1;
   final static Object o2;
}

If both fields are lacking an initialization, one error is reported against
the field, the other against the class.

While non-static fields correctly have the option of being reported against
an explicit constructor, which doesn&apos;t hold for static fields, there is
no reasons, why an error should be flagged against the class rather than
the field itself.</thetext>
